The EU AI Act: What to Know

The EU AI Act is the world’s first comprehensive AI regulation, ensuring AI systems deployed in the EU are safe, transparent, and respect fundamental rights. Adopted in 2024, the Act introduces a risk-based framework with phased implementation:

»	Mid-2025: Banned AI systems (e.g., social scoring, manipulative AI) must be removed; transparency obligations for limited-risk AI (e.g., deepfakes, chatbots) take effect.
»	August 2026: High-risk AI providers must implement risk management, oversight, and data governance; critical AI must be registered in the EU database.
»	August 2027: Full enforcement begins, including audits and penalties.

To ensure your firm is ready to comply with the EU AI Act, please consider the following:

Classify AI Systems Based on EU Risk Categories

»	Start by identifying and documenting your firm’s AI systems to build an internal AI inventory to track use cases and classify risk accurately
»	Identify if your AI use case falls under Unacceptable Risk (banned), High Risk (strict controls), Limited Risk (transparency required), or Minimal Risk (few obligations).
»	For Unacceptable Risk AI, ensure immediate removal by mid-2025 (e.g., social scoring systems, manipulative AI, real-time biometric surveillance — except in narrow law enforcement cases).
»	For High-Risk AI (used in healthcare, finance, law enforcement, employment), prepare for compliance with risk assessments, human oversight, and transparency rules by August 2026.
»	For Limited Risk AI (chatbots, deepfakes), implement clear user disclosure mechanisms.
»	For Minimal Risk AI (spam filters, video game AI), monitor for future regulatory changes but no immediate action is required.

Implement Risk Management & Governance Frameworks (High-Risk AI)

»	Establish an AI risk management policy to address bias, discrimination, and cybersecurity risks.
»	Conduct and document risk assessments before AI deployment and regularly after.
»	Ensure systems are designed with safety, fundamental rights, and ethical considerations in mind.
»	Ensure third-party AI vendors comply with AI Act requirements, including data security and governance.



Strengthen Data Governance & Security Controls

»	Train AI models only on high-quality, representative, and non-biased datasets.
»	Document AI model training sources, methodologies, and data lineage for auditability.
»	Implement cybersecurity protections against data poisoning, adversarial attacks, and model manipulation.
»	Integrate AI data governance with existing GDPR, DORA, and sectoral data policies.

Establish Human Oversight & Accountability Mechanisms

»	Design AI systems so that humans remain “in the loop” for sensitive decisions (e.g., hiring, lending, law enforcement).
»	Define roles and responsibilities for AI system supervision and intervention.
»	Train staff on AI oversight responsibilities and ethical use.

Conduct Robust Testing, Validation & Monitoring

»	Perform pre-deployment testing and validation to ensure safety, accuracy, and reliability.
»	Implement continuous monitoring processes to detect AI drift, bias, or performance issues post-deployment.
»	Retrain models periodically to maintain compliance and reliability.

Prepare for Incident Reporting & Compliance Audits

»	Set up mechanisms to report serious AI-related incidents and malfunctions to EU regulators.
»	Maintain detailed documentation and technical files for each high-risk AI system.
»	Be prepared for periodic audits, compliance checks, and corrective action requests by national regulators or the European AI Office.

Address Foundation Models & General Purpose AI (GPAI)

»	If providing or using large-scale general-purpose AI models (e.g., GPT, Gemini), comply with transparency, cybersecurity, and energy efficiency reporting requirements.
»	For high-impact GPAI models (posing systemic risk), prepare for additional compliance measures, including stricter testing, documentation, and EU registration obligations.


