EU’s Digital Operational Resiliency Act: What to Know
The Digital Operational Resilience Act (DORA), effective January 17, 2025, introduces broad new requirements for financial entities operating in the EU to strengthen their ability to prevent, withstand, and recover from ICT-related disruptions. Covered firms must implement a robust ICT risk management framework, report significant incidents within strict timelines, conduct regular resilience testing, and manage risks from third-party technology providers. DORA creates a unified standard for digital operational resilience across the financial sector, applying to banks, investment firms, insurers, and critical service providers.

To ensure your firm is ready to comply with DORA, please consider the following:

Implement an ICT Risk Management Framework
»	Implement a documented ICT risk management framework tailored to your organization's size, services, and risk profile.
»	Clearly define roles and responsibilities for ICT risk within the governance structure (including board and senior management oversight).
»	Identify, assess, and continuously monitor ICT risks, including emerging threats and vulnerabilities.
»	Maintain an updated inventory of ICT assets and classify them by criticality.
»	Ensure appropriate security controls (e.g., access controls, encryption, backup and recovery) are in place.
»	Ensure business continuity and disaster recovery plans include ICT-specific scenarios and are tested regularly.

Establish ICT-Related Incident Reporting Procedures
»	Establish internal procedures to detect, classify, and escalate ICT-related incidents promptly.
»	Use DORA’s incident classification criteria (e.g., number of clients affected, duration, data loss) to determine if an incident qualifies as major.
»	Notify competent authorities of a major ICT-related incident as follows:
o	Initial notification within 4 hours of classification as a major incident and not later than 24 hours.
o	Intermediate report within 72 hours after the initial notification.
o	Final report within 1-month, detailing root cause, impact, and remediation.
»	Maintain a central incident log and post-incident analysis process to identify root causes and prevent recurrence.
»	Review and update incident handling procedures at least annually.
Build a Structured Digital Operational Resilience Testing Program
»	Design a multi-layered testing program including vulnerability scanning, network security assessments, and scenario-based simulations.
»	Include advanced Threat-Led Penetration Testing (TLPT) every 3 years for entities designated as critical.
»	Ensure testing covers systems, applications, and third-party services that support critical or important functions.
»	Track and remediate any vulnerabilities or weaknesses discovered through testing.
»	Document testing results and share findings with senior management and internal audit functions.

Strengthen Oversight of Third-Party ICT Services Providers
»	Maintain a current register of all ICT third-party service providers, especially those supporting critical or important functions.
»	Conduct risk-based due diligence before engaging a new ICT third party.
»	Ensure contracts include clear provisions for:
o	Data protection and security controls
o	Sub-outsourcing conditions
o	Audit rights and access to information
o	Termination and exit support provisions
»	Continuously monitor service performance and risk exposure throughout the vendor lifecycle.
»	Develop and test exit and continuity strategies for critical third-party services.

Actively Participate and Utilize Cyber Threat Information Sharing
»	Evaluate participation in information-sharing initiatives that support collective cyber threat intelligence.
»	Ensure all shared information complies with confidentiality requirements, data protection laws, and competition rules.
»	Define and document internal procedures for receiving, analyzing, and acting on shared cyber threat and vulnerability information.

Ensure Governance and Oversight 
»	Assign ultimate responsibility for ICT risk management and digital resilience to the management body.
»	Ensure the risk management strategy explicitly addresses ICT and cyber risks.
»	Provide ongoing training to board members and staff on DORA obligations and digital risk awareness.
»	Embed ICT resilience into internal control frameworks and risk appetite statements.
»	Regularly audit DORA compliance and report findings to the board or senior management.





